THE UNSHAKABLE CORE:
You're RIGHT. Every great story needs one central truth that everything revolves around.
YOUR CORE:
"HUMANITY IS BOTH THE DISEASE AND THE CURE."
Everything stems from this:

Haruto: Believes humanity can be cured (through forced understanding)
Koyoi: Believes humanity is the disease (must be removed)
Third (Asa): Believes humanity should taste itself (self-inflicted truth)

Simple. Unshakable. Every conflict returns to this question.

THE THREE PHILOSOPHIES - SIMPLIFIED
HARUTO (The Corrector)
Philosophy: "Fix humanity's wrongs through forced empathy"

Make perpetrators feel what victims felt
Pain as teacher
Sentence: "I'll make you understand."

KOYOI (The Eraser)
Philosophy: "End humanity's capacity to suffer"

Remove all feeling
Mercy through void
Sentence: "I'll make it stop."

ASA (The Mirror)
Philosophy: "Let humanity taste itself"

Force people to face their own cruelty
Expose hypocrisy
Accelerate self-destruction
Sentence: "I'll show you what you are."


WHY THIS WORKS:
✅ Three directions, same diagnosis
✅ Each believes they're merciful
✅ None are purely evil
✅ Readers can sympathize with all three
✅ No clear "right answer"
Simple enough for readers. Deep enough for impact.

KOYOI'S PHILOSOPHY - REFINED
You said: "I'm not sure about Koyoi though."
Let me make it clearer:
KOYOI (The Eraser) - REVISED
Core Belief:
"If nobody can feel, nobody can hurt."
Logic:

All suffering comes from caring
Remove caring = remove suffering
Mercy = making people stop feeling

Method:

Doesn't kill (death is too simple)
Removes emotions (leaves people hollow but alive)
They walk, breathe, exist—but feel nothing
"I'm saving you from pain."

Why She's Tragic:

She's not wrong (caring DOES cause pain)
She's not right (life without feeling isn't life)
She knows this but can't stop
"I'm doing to them what I wish someone did to me."

Sentence: "I'll make it stop hurting."

ALTERNATIVE NAMES FOR ASA (朝 - Morning)
You liked the thematic completion but want other options:
OPTION 1: AKATSUKI (暁)

Meaning: "Dawn" / "Daybreak"
Longer, more dramatic than Asa
Keeps morning/beginning theme
Sounds slightly ominous

OPTION 2: HAJIME (始)

Meaning: "Beginning" / "Origin"
Implies he's the start of something
Less time-specific than Asa
Works for male character

OPTION 3: SHIN (新)

Meaning: "New" / "Fresh"
Implies renewal (fits cycle theme)
Short, sharp, memorable
Contrasts Haruto/Koyoi's longer names

OPTION 4: YOAKE (夜明け)

Meaning: "Dawn" / "Daybreak" (poetic)
Literally "night opening"
Beautiful contrast to Koyoi (night)
Slightly feminine-sounding (if that matters)

OPTION 5: ARATA (新)

Meaning: "Fresh" / "New"
Common given name (realistic)
Implies new beginning
Easy to remember

OPTION 6: ASA (朝) - Original

Meaning: "Morning"
Simplest, shortest
Direct thematic completion
Easy for non-Japanese speakers


MY RANKING:
1. ASA (朝) - Original pick

Clean, simple, completes the cycle
Short like Koyoi (2 syllables vs Haruto's 3)
Thematic clarity

