Let me break down the style we should use:

TONE & PROSE:
HARD-HITTING, GROUNDED, CINEMATIC
What We AVOID:
❌ Purple prose (flowery, over-descriptive)
❌ Poetic metaphors (unless earned)
❌ Excessive adjectives
❌ Anime clichés ("power of friendship," over-explanation)
❌ Melodrama (telling readers how to feel)
What We USE:
✅ Short, punchy sentences (especially in action)
✅ Show, don't tell (actions reveal character)
✅ Internal monologue (Haruto's philosophy woven naturally)
✅ Dialogue-driven (conversations reveal worldview)
✅ Visceral descriptions (violence feels real, not stylized)
✅ Silence matters (pauses, what's NOT said)

REFERENCE STYLES:
CHAINSAW MAN (Fujimoto):

Brutal simplicity
Violence is matter-of-fact
Emotional beats hit without warning
Minimal exposition

TOKYO GHOUL (Ishida):

Psychological depth
Internal conflict externalized
Philosophy through action
Tragic inevitability

OYASUMI PUNPUN (Asano):

Raw, uncomfortable realism
Society's rot shown, not told
Characters deeply flawed
No easy answers


EXAMPLE COMPARISON:
BAD (Purple Prose):

"Haruto's heart shattered into a million pieces as tears streamed down his anguished face, the weight of unbearable grief crushing his very soul like a vice of eternal torment."

GOOD (Our Style):

"Haruto stopped walking. Stood there. Stared at nothing. Then his legs gave out."


ACTION STYLE:
BAD (Over-explained):

"Haruto activated his incredible speed ability, moving so fast that the world around him seemed to slow to a crawl as he dodged the incoming attack with perfect precision."

GOOD (Cinematic):

"The knife came at him. World slowed. Two seconds. He stepped left. Knife passed. Grabbed the wrist. Twisted. Snap."


DIALOGUE STYLE:
BAD (Exposition dump):

"Shiori, I've been thinking about how society has failed us and created a system where people no longer care about each other's suffering, which is why I believe—"

GOOD (Natural):

"Do people actually change?"
"Only when forced."
"So suffering is necessary?"
"Understanding is. People don't change until they feel consequences."


