THE FLAW I MADE:
I went too far in the opposite direction. I stripped out style completely.
The issue:

"Haruto stopped walking. Stood there. Stared at nothing." = BLAND
No rhythm, no voice, no flavor
Reads like stage directions, not prose

What's missing:

Personality in narration (whose POV? How do THEY see the world?)
Rhythm variation (mix short punches with longer flows)
Specific details (not generic, PRECISE observations)
Earned poetry (when emotion peaks, language can too)


WEB SEARCH - LIGHT NOVEL WRITING STYLEsuccessful light novels writing style prose techniques Japanese fiction10 resultsHow to Write a Light Novel - LivingWriter Writing Bloglivingwriter.comHow to Write a Light Novel (2024 Guide for Authors)bloggingyourpassion.comWhat Is a Light Novel? Exploring Japan's Literary Cousin to Mangadashtoon.comHow to Write a Light Novel: A Comprehensive Guidevoxtury.comUnlocking Creativity: Essential Tips for Writing a Light Novelpublishingpush.comHow to Write a light Novel [1/2] - Forum - Anime News Networkanimenewsnetwork.comLight novel - Wikipediawikipedia.orgJapanese literature - Wikipediawikipedia.org5 Things You Should Know About Japanese Literaturejapanobjects.comAdvice Thread on Writing Light Novels and Webnovels | Kindle Forumkboards.comWHAT I LEARNED FROM RESEARCH:
KEY LIGHT NOVEL CHARACTERISTICS:
✅ Dialogue-heavy (conversations drive story)
✅ Simple BUT NOT BLAND language (accessible, not dumbed-down)
✅ Action-oriented (things happen, constantly moving forward)
✅ Internal monologue (character voice matters)
✅ Short paragraphs (digestible, fast-paced)
✅ Evocative details (specific, vivid, not generic)
✅ Character voice (POV character's personality colors narration)

THE CORRECTED STYLE:
REVISED EXAMPLE (PROPER BALANCE):
BAD (What I did):

"Haruto stopped walking. Stood there. Stared at nothing."

GOOD (What it should be):

"Haruto's legs stopped obeying him. He stood in the middle of the sidewalk—people flowing around him like he was a stone in a river—and stared at the cracks in the pavement. Three years of philosophy classes, and the only thought in his head was: She's gone."

Why this works:

Specific detail (cracks in pavement, stone in river)
Character voice (his thoughts, his education, his irony)
Rhythm variation (longer sentence followed by short gut-punch)
Emotion shown (not told)


ACTION EXAMPLE (REVISED):
BAD:

"The knife came at him. World slowed. Two seconds. He stepped left. Knife passed. Grabbed the wrist. Twisted. Snap."

GOOD:

"The knife came fast—too fast for most people. For Haruto, the world stretched like taffy. Two seconds of perfect clarity. He watched the blade's trajectory, saw the fear in the man's eyes (he knew this wouldn't work), stepped left with a dancer's grace he'd never had before. The knife kissed air. Haruto's hand closed around the wrist. Twisted. The snap was louder than he expected."

Why this works:

Specific metaphor (taffy, dancer's grace)
Character observation (saw the fear)
Sensory detail (snap was louder than expected)
Maintains speed (still fast, but with TEXTURE)


DIALOGUE EXAMPLE (REVISED):
BAD:

"Do people actually change?"
"Only when forced."

GOOD:

Shiori looked up from her book. "Do you think people actually change?"
Haruto didn't answer immediately. He watched the café window—couple arguing outside, voices muted by glass. "Only when forced. When they can't pretend anymore."
"So suffering is necessary?"
"Understanding is." He turned back to her. "People don't change until they feel real consequences. Not abstract. Real."

Why this works:

Scene setting (café window, couple arguing)
Character action (looking, watching, pausing)
Rhythm (mix of short/long)
Subtext (he's watching people lie to each other)


POWER CLARIFICATION:
PHANTOM STRIKE:

Haruto's attacks phase through defenses
Punch goes through raised guard, hits chest anyway
Not speed—ignores barriers
Shiori explains: "You exist in two states. Solid and not. Your strikes choose which."

DASH IMPACT:

Haruto moves with extreme speed
Shockwave left behind where he was
Delayed explosion (0.5 seconds after)
Shiori explains: "You're moving faster than reality updates. The world catches up violently."


PROPOSAL LINE - REVISED:
OLD:

"When I thought I was dying, I didn't think about my parents. Or my sibling. Or revenge. I thought about never getting to ask you this."

NEW:

"When I was dying in that alley, I had one thought. Not about my parents working themselves to death. Not about my sibling choosing a rope over tomorrow. Not even about making those men pay."
[His voice cracks]
"I thought: I can't lose another person to this shallow, ruthless society. Not you. Not without telling you—without asking you—"

Better because:
✅ References specific tragedies
✅ "Shallow, ruthless society" = his worldview
✅ More emotional weight
✅ Longer build before the ask

ENDING - REVISED (NO LIGHT):
WHAT HAPPENS:
Ring slides onto her finger.
The bond seals:

Ring tightens (physical sensation)
Her form becomes more solid (temperature drops)
She gasps (didn't need to breathe, now does)
Her shadow appears (hadn't cast one before)

After:
They stand together at water's edge.
Haruto: "What now?"
Shiori: "Now we live. As long as we can."
Haruto extends hand behind him (love language—piggyback gesture).
She understands immediately.
Shiori: "You're ridiculous."
Haruto: "I know."
She steps forward—
BUT:
Instead of climbing on his back, she wraps around his arms (transformation).
Visual:

Her form becomes translucent
Flows around his arms like water
Eyes shift to pale silver-gold
Hair tips turn white, float slightly
Her shadow merges with his (now one shadow, not two)

His voice (changed slightly—hers underneath):
"Let's go home."

FINAL IMAGE:
Haruto walks away from lake.
Single figure.
Single shadow (but if you look closely—two overlapped).
Mt. Fuji reflected in still water behind him.
Sunrise breaking.
THE END - FRAGMENT 詩

