NARRATIVE STRATEGY:
CHAPTER 1:

❌ No names revealed yet
Referred to as: "the young man," "the man," "Kenji," "the roommate"
Creates mystery (Who is this person? What happened to them?)
Readers don't know protagonist's name until...

CHAPTER 2:

✅ Names revealed when we flashback to "TWO MONTHS AGO"
Opens with normal life
"Haruto Nakamura sat in the back of the lecture hall..."
"Shiori was waiting for him at the café..."
Readers finally learn WHO these people are
Context fills in (oh, HE'S the protagonist, SHE'S the victim)


WHY THIS WORKS:
✅ Chapter 1 = Hook (mystery, violence, intrigue)
✅ Chapter 2 = Context (names, relationships, humanity)
✅ Creates two different emotional experiences:

Ch1: Cold, detached hunter (who IS this person?)
Ch2: Warm, philosophical student (oh... this is who he WAS)

✅ Contrast hits harder:

See the monster first
Then see the human he used to be
Tragedy becomes visceral


EXAMPLE OPENING FOR CHAPTER 2:

TWO MONTHS AGO
Haruto Nakamura sat in the back of the lecture hall, staring at the professor's slideshow on utilitarianism without really seeing it. His notebook was open, pen in hand, but he hadn't written anything in twenty minutes.
His phone buzzed. A text from Shiori:
Done with class yet? I'm at the café. Got your usual.
He smiled—small, genuine, the kind of expression that would become impossible in two months' time—and typed back:
Five minutes. Save me a seat.

This way:

Readers finally get names
See them as people (not hunter/victim)
Makes the tragedy hit different


